z, Klaus, Kurt, Otto, Reinhold.","German:","northern variant of   Kastner   in either of its senses (‘steward’ or ‘joiner’)."]}]},{"name":"Béatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ou","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Scholar’, specifically a Confucian scholar."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Garne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin probably an occupational name for a grower or seller of pomegranates (from a metathesized form of Old French <i>(pome) grenate</i>, Latin <i>pomum granatum</i> ‘fruit full of seeds’). The name of the red-coloured precious stone derives from the same source, in reference to the fruit's bright red colour, and use as a modern first name may have been inspired by the adoption of other terms denoting gemstones as female names. It may also in part reflect the fame of the British field marshal  Sir Garnet Wolseley  (  1833–1913 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Garnett","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin probably an occupational name for a grower or seller of pomegranates (from a metathesized form of Old French <i>(pome) grenate</i>, Latin <i>pomum granatum</i> ‘fruit full of seeds’). The name of the red-coloured precious stone derives from the same source, in reference to the fruit's bright red colour, and use as a modern first name may have been inspired by the adoption of other terms denoting gemstones as female names. It may also in part reflect the fame of the British field marshal  Sir Garnet Wolseley  (  1833–1913 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Béatrix ou Garne de Cosnes was born in 1110, in Vierzon, Cher, Centre, France, her father, Hugues Le Manceau De Cosnes, was 28 and her mother, Béatrice De Toucy, was 14. She had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Geoffroy de Donzy III, Baron de Donzy. She died in 1151, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1110–1151":"1110–1151","1118–1185":"1118–1185","1094–1157":"1094–1157","1131–1187":"1131–1187","1132–1189":"1132–1189","1135–1175":"1135–1175","–Male":"Surnud","1082–1139":"1082–1139","1097–1151":"1097–1151","1110":"1110","1132":"1132","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1175":"1175","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1151":"1151","1094":"1094","1082":"1082","1118":"1118","1139":"1139","1135":"1135","1157":"1157","1189":"1189","ABT 1135":"umbes 1135","Cosne-Cours-sur-Loire, Nièvre, Bourgogne, France":"Cosne-Cours-sur-Loire, Nièvre, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Prantsusmaa","of, Vierzon, Cher, France":"Vierzon, Cher, Centre, Prantsusmaa","Donzy, Cosne-Cours-sur-Loire, Nièvre, Bourgogne, France":"Donzy, Cosne-Cours-sur-Loire, Nièvre, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Decize, France":"Decize, Nièvre, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1110–1151":"1110–1151","1118–1185":"1118–1185","1094–1157":"1094–1157","1131–1187":"1131–1187","1132–1189":"1132–1189","1135–1175":"1135–1175","–Male":"Kuollut","1082–1139":"1082–1139","1097–1151":"1097–1151","1110":"1110","1132":"1132","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1175":"1175","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1151":"1151","1094":"1094","1082":"1082","1118":"1118","1139":"1139","1135":"1135","1157":"1157","1189":"1189","ABT 1135":"noin 1135","Cosne-Cours-sur-Loire, Nièvre, Bourgogne, France":"Cosne-Cours-sur-Loire, Nièvre, Bou